  lectureDescription: "<h1>Lecture Summary: GameManager and Singleton Pattern</h1><p>In
    this lecture, we created a <strong>GameManager </strong>class to handle the core
    game logic and learned about the <strong>Singleton pattern </strong>to ensure
    clean and efficient code. Instead of dragging multiple references for each grid
    position, the singleton pattern allows us to maintain a single instance of the
    GameManager that's globally accessible.</p><p>We implemented the singleton by
    defining a <strong>static Instance </strong>property with a <strong>public getter
    </strong>and a <strong>private setter</strong>. The Instance is initialized in
    the Awake method and includes a safety check to ensure only one instance exists.</p><p>With
    this setup, the grid positions can call <strong>GameManager.Instance.ClickedOnGridPosition(x,
    y)</strong> when clicked, allowing us to handle click events in the GameManager.
    This approach keeps our <strong>code clean </strong>and avoids redundant references.
    Everything is set up and working perfectly!</p>\r\n<p>C# Course - Singleton Pattern
